    "eyebrow": "Cause Analysis",
    "num": "10",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">10</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cause Analysis</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Mexican Centralism vs. Texan Autonomy</h2><ul><li>Mexico shifted from federalism to centralism, reducing Texas’s self-rule</li><li>Settlers wanted local control over laws and governance</li><li>Centralist policies included military enforcement and suspension of local legislatures</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Mexico’s political shift to centralism removed local powers in Texas, provoking resistance from settlers who valued autonomy and self-governance, a key cause of the revolution. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Examine the impact of Mexico’s 1835 centralist constitution on Texas governance.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explain how centralism conflicted with settlers’ political expectations.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid confusing federalism and centralism; they represent different governance models.</p></div></div>",
