      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Mexico’s political shift to centralism removed local powers in Texas, provoking resistance from settlers who valued autonomy and self-governance, a key cause of the revolution.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Mexico shifted from federalism to centralism, reducing Texas’s self-rule</li><li>Settlers wanted local control over laws and governance</li><li>Centralist policies included military enforcement and suspension of local legislatures</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Examine the impact of Mexico’s 1835 centralist constitution on Texas governance.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain how centralism conflicted with settlers’ political expectations.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid confusing federalism and centralism; they represent different governance models.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p>"
